Maya Bay left me with some seriously mixed feelings. On one hand, it was easily the most beautiful beach I have ever laid eyes on. On the other hand, we arrived at 7AM and it already felt crowded.. by 9AM it was getting zoo-ish. Then on the other other hand (so many mixed feelings I had to grow more hands), the tourists there were putting on a serious show with some of the most incredible photo shoots I've seen to date. Everyone was behaving as though they were in a bikini calendar: rolling around in the waves, splashing the water, and flicking their hair. Selfie sticks were out of control. Most people did nothing but take photos of themselves. What ever happened to going somewhere so incredible to just sit back and enjoy it?

Held yearly, on the evening of the twelfth lunar month (usually in November), at the end of the rainy season when the full-moon lights up the sky. So the makara in this picture is the toothy girl vomiting out the seven-headed naga (divine snakelike creature). The possible symbolism of that here is that the Naga represented Burma, and the Makara represented the (former) kingdom of Lanna, holding the Burmese within its jaws. But the naga can also represent the human mind while the makara represents sin, that has the power, if unchecked, to control the mind. What does vulnerability means to you?

I accidentaly found this speaker with an interesting concept of negative emotions when randomly browsed TedTalks this morning.

Here's what I found.

Vulnerability is

The willingness to say I Love You first
The willingness to do something where there is no guarantee
The willingness to invest in a relationship that may or maynot workout
To love with our whole heart even there is no guarantee of being returned.

Vulnerability is not a weakness.

Vulnerability is the core of shame, fear and struggle for worthiness but it's also a birthplace of joy, creativity, belonging and love

So why don't we fully embrace our vulnerability?
Believe that what made us vulnerable, would also made us beautiful.

The power of vulnerability
Brene Brown.

The Twenty-six Martyrs of Japan (Nihon Nijuroku Seijin) were a group of Christians who were executed by crucifixion on February 5, 1597, at Nagasaki.
*
The 26 people, a mixture of native Japanese Christians and European priests (20 Japanese, 4 Spaniards, 1 Mexican and one Indian) had been arrested in Kyoto and Osaka on the order of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, the national ruler, for preaching Christianity.
*
They were imprisoned, then later marched through the snow to Nagasaki, so that their execution might serve as a deterrent to Nagasaki's large Christian population.
*
Hung up on 26 crosses with chains and ropes, the Christians were lanced to death in front of a large crowd on Nishizaka Hill.
*
The main monument with and extensive bronze depicting the Twenty-Six Martyrs, was designed by Japanese sculptor, Yasutake Funakoshi. The work took Funakoshi 4 years to complete.

CAPTION: Every day for the past 11 years, Mr. Ann has been visiting the same spot in the Mangrove forest across the river from the Krabi Town pier where he's befriended a family of monkeys. He brings with him a bag full of bananas and coaxes them aboard his long tail boat so that tourists can feed them. Most Thai natives are afraid of being bitten by monkeys but not Mr. Ann. He's become somewhat of a celebrity among the boat drivers on the pier. Some even try to impersonate him, attempting to steal his business. But according to him, he is the most trusted guide on the river. During the 2004 tsunami that wrecked the Thailand coast, Mr Ann found himself in a tough position with a boat full of tourists just off shore. When he noticed the ocean quickly receding he had the foresight to head out to deep sea to ride out the massive swells instead of risking being crushed on the beach despite the protest of his passengers who wanted to return home to check on the safety of their families. He likely saved their lives.

Day 3: Koh Phi Phi Island

As I stepped out off the ferry, the view of the island took my breath away. The hills surrounding the islands were majestic!!
Koh Phi Phi on its own is more of a transition to the other islands nearby, I would say 98% of the people I saw were all tourist! 
So expect again, things to be tourist priced. The island does have one thing right, hospitality. Every other face I came across was ready to give directions where to go and suggestions what to eat! There was no sense of bias and you could feel how communal things were.
Mind you, being a tourist island, the multiple bars and mini clubs were all competing on who had the best sound system as soon as the sun was setting.

Loy Krathong is one of Thailand‚Äôs most popular festivals, celebrated annually on the full moon of the 12th lunar month ‚Äì Nov. 25 this year. The celebration is an expression of gratitude to the goddess of water, a thanksgiving for her providing this most important of resources to the people.

All along waterways throughout the kingdom, families and couples gather to float (or ‚Äúloy‚Äù) lotus shaped receptacles (or ‚Äúkrathongs‚Äù), beautifully decorated with flowers, candles and joss sticks. The flames from the candles signify longevity, a release of sin and fulfillment of wishes. Hence the act of floating the krathong, which has also become a symbolic act for couples.
It is said that couples who float krathongs together will stay together forever. <3
